commentary: Aamer Yamin to Williamson, OUT what just happened? Williamson has bunted a catch to deep square leg. A good length delivery on middle and leg, Williamson, it seems, is caught in between a hoick and a flick, in between going after it with everything or just clipping it for one. In the end, he does neither. The ball just lobs to the fielder. Uncharacteristic, strange

commentary: Faheem Ashraf to Santner, 1 run, OUT looks like Santner could be run out first ball. Yes he is. Gets a short ball going across him. It's skidding fast as he pulls and he chips it wide of long-on off the high part of the bat. This mistimed shot allows them a thought about the second run - which CDG calls for and is close to completing. Nawaz fires the throw to the striker's end on the bounce. Sarfraz picks up and beats Santner's dive by a long way

commentary: Santner to Haris Sohail, OUT that increasing asking rate has resulted in a wicket. Nicely tossed up from Santner, down leg, 77 kph after a 96 kph first delivery. Haris comes down, but is deceived by that lack of pace as he tries to loft the ball straight. Santner's direction of spin means the ball was always going to skew away to long-on if he didn't time it, as is the case here. But a lovely rearguard effort from Haris

commentary: Santner to Shadab Khan, OUT is that the game? It's another lovely display of defensive, but attacking spin bowling. He knows Shadab is going to come so he tosses it up, but wide outside off. Shadab runs down, looking to hit the ball over cover. Instead, it skews off the outside half to short third man. Just like how de Grandhomme got out to Chahal in the second ODI in Pune last year. It's a defensive attacking option, oxymoron-ish as it may be

commentary: Henry to Rumman Raees, OUT and that's the game. It doesn't go to the last over, but that was a sensational finish to the ODI series. A short slower delivery outside off, Raees swats it away towards midwicket, who keeps his eyes on the ball and takes a reverse-cupped catch. New Zealand complete a 5-0 sweep in the ODIs
